[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I write not these things to shame you.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I write these things not as one making you ashamed, but I am warning you as beloved children.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The mingled irony and reproach of the preceding verses here ceases, and from indignant expostulation the writer now turns to make a tender and touching appeal to their better nature and their sympathy. This abrupt and sudden change in style is characteristic of the writings of St. Paul. Similar passages are nowhere to be found in the writings of the other Apostles. The following verses to the end of this chapter soften the severity of this early part of the Epistle by explaining in what spirit he has written, and the right which he has as their “father in the faith” to so address them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 4:14-16",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 4:14-16",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I write not these things to shame you ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Publicly to disgrace you, and stain your credit with other churches; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "but as my beloved sons I warn you ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Show you in a mild and tender way what is wrong in your conduct, and put you in mind of your duty. It is with admirable prudence and sweetness the apostle adds this, to prevent any unkind construction of his words. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For though you have ten thousand instructers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— To advance you in the knowledge of Christ; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "yet have ye not many fathers; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "to convert you to Christ: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for in Christ Jesus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— By his blessing upon my labours; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I have begotten you through the gospel ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Been the first instrument of your conversion. This excludes, not only Apollos, his successor, but also Silas and Timothy, his companions. And the relation between a spiritual father and his children brings with it an inexpressible nearness and affection. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Be ye followers of me ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In that spirit and behaviour which I have so largely declared.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
